defs.docs:
pcap is a packet capture library available on Linux, Windows and Mac. This
 crate supports creating and configuring capture contexts, sniffing packets,
 sending packets to interfaces, listing devices, and recording packet captures
 to pcap-format dump files.

defs.docs: A network device name and (potentially) pcap's description of it.

defs.name: lookup
defs.docs:
Returns the default Device suitable for captures according to pcap_lookupdev,
 or an error from pcap.

defs.name: list
defs.docs: Returns a vector of `Device`s known by pcap via pcap_findalldevs.

defs.name: Packet
defs.docs: Represents a packet returned from pcap.

defs.name: PacketHeader
defs.docs: Represents a packet header provided by pcap, including the timeval, caplen and len.

defs.name: Inactive
defs.docs: Phantom type representing an inactive capture handle.

defs.name: Active
defs.docs: Phantom type representing an active capture handle.

defs.name: Offline
defs.docs:
Phantom type representing an offline capture handle, from a pcap dump file.
 Implements `Activated` because it behaves nearly the same as a live handle.

defs.name: Dead
defs.docs:
Phantom type representing a dead capture handle.  This can be use to create
 new save files that are not generated from an active capture.
 Implements `Activated` because it behaves nearly the same as a live handle.

defs.name: State
defs.docs:
`Capture`s can be in different states at different times, and in these states they
 may or may not have particular capabilities. This trait is implemented by phantom
 types which allows us to punt these invariants to the type system to avoid runtime
 errors.

defs.name: Capture
defs.docs:
This is a pcap capture handle which is an abstraction over the `pcap_t` provided by pcap.
 There are many ways to instantiate and interact with a pcap handle, so phantom types are
 used to express these behaviors.

defs.name: from_file
defs.docs: Opens an offline capture handle from a pcap dump file, given a path.

defs.name: from_file_with_precision
defs.value:
fn

(path: P, precision: Precision) -> Result, Error>
defs.docs:
Opens an offline capture handle from a pcap dump file, given a path.
 Takes an additional precision argument specifying the time stamp precision desired.

defs.name: from_raw_fd
defs.docs: Opens an offline capture handle from a pcap dump file, given a file descriptor.

defs.name: from_device
defs.docs:
Opens a capture handle for a device. You can pass a `Device` or an `&str` device
 name here. The handle is inactive, but can be activated via `.open()`.

defs.name: open
defs.docs:
Activates an inactive capture created from `Capture::from_device()` or returns
 an error.

defs.name: timeout
defs.docs:
Set the read timeout for the Capture. By default, this is 0, so it will block
 indefinitely.

defs.name: tstamp_type
defs.docs: Set the time stamp type to be used by a capture device.

defs.name: promisc
defs.docs: Set promiscuous mode on or off. By default, this is off.

defs.name: rfmon
defs.docs: Set rfmon mode on or off. The default is maintained by pcap.

defs.name: buffer_size
defs.docs: Set the buffer size for incoming packet data.

defs.name: precision
defs.docs: Set the time stamp precision returned in captures.

defs.name: snaplen
defs.docs:
Set the snaplen size (the maximum length of a packet captured into the buffer).
 Useful if you only want certain headers, but not the entire packet.

defs.name: list_datalinks
defs.docs: List the datalink types that this captured device supports.

defs.name: set_datalink
defs.value: fn (&mut self, linktype: Linktype) -> Result<(), Error>
defs.docs: Set the datalink type for the current capture handle.

defs.name: get_datalink
defs.docs: Get the current datalink type for this capture handle.

defs.name: savefile
defs.docs:
Create a `Savefile` context for recording captured packets using this `Capture`'s
 configurations.

defs.name: next
defs.docs: Blocks until a packet is returned from the capture handle or an error occurs.

defs.name: filter
defs.docs:
Adds a filter to the capture using the given BPF program string. Internally
 this is compiled using `pcap_compile()`.
